hints_latex:
Recall that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle f^{-1}(D)
\end{align*}

is the pre-image of the set $D$, that is the set containing all the
elements that are mapped by $f$ into the set $D$ and that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle f(C)
\end{align*}

is the image of the set $C$, that is the set all the images of elements
of the set $C$.

sols_latex:
\begin{align*}
f^{-1}(D) = \{ a \in A \mid f(a) \in D \}
\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}
f(C) = \{ f(c)\mid c\in C \}.
\end{align*}

statement_latex:
Let

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle f : A \to B
\end{align*} be a function and let

\begin{align*}
C \subseteq A
\end{align*} and $D \subseteq B$. Define the sets

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle f^{-1} (D)
\end{align*} and $\displaystyle f (C)$.
